Guard the sound data pointer before it is loaded

Startup() installs the timer handler inside StartAdLib(), several hundred
milliseconds before it calls LoadSoundData(). In between, every timer tick runs
PCSpeakerService(), which dereferences soundDataPtr[activeSoundIndex] without
checking it.

On DOS that was harmless. The array is static, so it started as a null far
pointer, and 0000:0000 in real mode is the interrupt vector table -- readable
memory holding values that were never going to equal END_SOUND. The read
returned junk, the comparison failed, and the game carried on.

With a modern memory map that same read is a fault on the very first tick. The
guard returns early, after gameTickCount has already been incremented, so the
game clock keeps its cadence and only the speaker work is skipped -- which is
exactly what happened before, just without reading the vector table to find out.

diff --git a/game1.c b/game1.c
index d887712..027948d 100644
--- a/game1.c
+++ b/game1.c
@@ -8051,6 +8051,14 @@ void PCSpeakerService(void)
         enableSpeaker = true;
     }
 
+    /*
+    PORT: soundDataPtr is still null here on the first few hundred ticks --
+    StartAdLib() installs this handler well before Startup() loads the sound
+    data. In real mode the null pointer aimed at 0000:0000, the interrupt
+    vector table, which read back harmless garbage. Here it faults.
+    */
+    if (soundDataPtr[activeSoundIndex] == NULL) return;
+
     if (*(soundDataPtr[activeSoundIndex] + soundCursor) == END_SOUND) {
         enableSpeaker = false;
         activeSoundPriority = 0;
